<div id="review_464714859" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/464714859" />
    <a title="Aaron Wolfson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4463803-aaron-wolfson"><img alt="Aaron Wolfson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1288072528p2/4463803.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/464714859?book_show_action=true">Nov 27, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aaron Wolfson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aaron Wolfson" href="/user/show/4463803-aaron-wolfson">Aaron Wolfson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer464714859" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13330638857780959379">Your Life&apos;s Task is to discover your uniqueness, and express it in your work, the work only you can do. And the way to do that is to submit to the process of Mastery.<br/><br/>The Life&apos;s Task is a concept I&apos;ve always believed in, but I&apos;ve never been able to articulate it as well as Greene, who himself is a Master storyteller and synthesizer of how humans operate.<br/><br/>But since this is my review, I&apos;ll give it a go anyway, with a nod to Greene, as I couch my formulations in his and bask in his reflected luminesc</span>
  <span id="freeText13330638857780959379" style="display:none">Your Life's Task is to discover your uniqueness, and express it in your work, the work only you can do. And the way to do that is to submit to the process of Mastery.<br /><br />The Life's Task is a concept I've always believed in, but I've never been able to articulate it as well as Greene, who himself is a Master storyteller and synthesizer of how humans operate.<br /><br />But since this is my review, I'll give it a go anyway, with a nod to Greene, as I couch my formulations in his and bask in his reflected luminescence.<br /><br />I believe that my particular combination of abilities, inclinations, and makeup (and yours!) are gifts. From God? Maybe. From my ancestors, via my genes? Well, certainly, to one degree or another. Wherever from, it seems clear, to be alive and unique and human is a miracle.<br /><br />I feel that to repay, or maybe instead, to give tribute to, these gifts, is my purpose in the world. I feel that this is what is meant by having a "calling." (Greene agrees, and points to the etymology of the term as proof.)<br /><br />OK, fine. But life's short. How best to pursue such a monumental, seemingly incredible task? By following the process, as laid down by the Masters who have come before.<br /><br />Greene's great achievement is to comb through these eminent examples, from both yesterday and today, and extract the key lessons, the milestones on the road to Mastery.<br /><br />In addition, he makes clear that there is nothing magical or unreachable about this process. It is already a part of all of us, just as our particular combination of abilities, inclinations, and makeup is unique in the world. It has never been seen before, nor will it again.<br /><br />What a shame not to cultivate that seed, to help it reach full flower, to let the miracle inside you simply pass the world by.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13330638857780959379" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


